window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["cardiomyopathies"]={"slug": "cardiomyopathies", "title": "Cardiomyopathies", "tagline": "A fellowship-level field guide to hypertrophic, restrictive/infiltrative, dilated, and arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathies: phenotyping, risk stratification, disease-modifying therapy, and family screening.", "level": 2, "readMin": 42, "takeaways": ["Phenotype first, etiology second: a thickened or restrictive-appearing ventricle demands you separate true myocyte hypertrophy (HCM), infiltration (amyloid, sarcoid, Fabry), and storage/pressure-overload mimics before you commit to therapy.", "Cardiac amyloidosis has moved from untreatable to treatable: recognize red flags, use technetium-PYP with mandatory light-chain screening to diagnose ATTR non-invasively, and start a disease-modifying agent (tafamidis, acoramidis, or vutrisiran) in ATTR-CM.", "HCM management is now three-pronged: relieve LVOT obstruction (beta-blockers, verapamil, disopyramide, mavacamten under REMS, septal reduction), prevent SCD using the ACC/AHA risk-factor model and ESC HCM Risk-SCD score, and screen the family.", "Distinguishing restrictive cardiomyopathy from constrictive pericarditis is one of the highest-yield hemodynamic problems in cardiology because constriction is surgically curable.", "Every newly diagnosed genetic or unexplained cardiomyopathy triggers first-degree family screening with a pedigree, clinical evaluation, and genetic testing of the proband to enable cascade testing."], "references": ["2024 AHA/ACC/AMSSM/HRS/PACES/SCMR Guideline for the Management of Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy", "2020 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Patients With Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy", "2023 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Cardiomyopathies", "EXPLORER-HCM and VALOR-HCM trials of mavacamten in obstructive HCM", "SEQUOIA-HCM trial of aficamten in obstructive HCM", "ATTR-ACT trial of tafamidis in transthyretin amyloid cardiomyopathy", "ATTRibute-CM trial of acoramidis in transthyretin amyloid cardiomyopathy", "HELIOS-B trial of vutrisiran in transthyretin amyloid cardiomyopathy", "ASNC/AHA/ACC and multisociety expert consensus recommendations on cardiac amyloidosis diagnosis with bone scintigraphy (technetium pyrophosphate imaging) and monoclonal protein screening", "2017 AHA/ACC/HRS Guideline for Management of Patients With Ventricular Arrhythmias and Prevention of Sudden Cardiac Death", "2014 HRS Expert Consensus Statement on the Diagnosis and Management of Arrhythmias Associated With Cardiac Sarcoidosis", "2019 HRS Expert Consensus Statement on Evaluation, Risk Stratification, and Management of Arrhythmogenic Cardiomyopathy"], "guidelines": [{"society": "AHA/ACC", "year": "2024", "text": "For symptomatic obstructive HCM, first-line therapy is a nonvasodilating beta-blocker titrated to effect; a nondihydropyridine calcium channel blocker (verapamil or diltiazem) is recommended if beta-blockers are ineffective or not tolerated."}, {"society": "AHA/ACC", "year": "2024", "text": "For obstructive HCM with persistent symptoms despite beta-blocker or calcium channel blocker, options include adding disopyramide, adding a cardiac myosin inhibitor (mavacamten), or referral for septal reduction therapy at an experienced center."}, {"society": "AHA/ACC", "year": "2024", "text": "SCD risk stratification integrates family history of SCD, maximal wall thickness >=30 mm, unexplained syncope, NSVT, LV apical aneurysm, LVEF <50%, and extensive LGE on CMR, applied through shared decision-making for primary-prevention ICD."}, {"society": "ESC", "year": "2023", "text": "Cardiomyopathies are classified by morphofunctional phenotype (HCM, DCM, NDLVC, RCM, ARVC); genetic testing of the proband and cascade clinical and genetic screening of relatives are recommended."}, {"society": "ASNC/AHA/ACC multisociety", "text": "Bone-avid radiotracer scintigraphy (PYP/DPD/HMDP) showing grade 2-3 myocardial uptake with negative monoclonal protein screening (serum/urine immunofixation and free light-chain ratio) establishes ATTR-CM without endomyocardial biopsy."}, {"society": "HFSA/ACC (trial-based)", "text": "Tafamidis is recommended in ATTR-CM to reduce all-cause mortality and cardiovascular hospitalization; acoramidis and vutrisiran are additional disease-modifying options approved for ATTR-CM."}, {"society": "HRS", "year": "2019", "text": "In arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy, restriction of competitive and high-intensity endurance exercise is advised, and ICD decisions weigh prior sustained VT/arrest against primary-prevention markers such as syncope, ventricular dysfunction, NSVT, and inducibility."}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 68-year-old man presents with progressive dyspnea and bilateral carpal tunnel syndrome treated 6 years ago. Echo shows LV wall thickness 16 mm, biatrial enlargement, a small pericardial effusion, and a global longitudinal strain pattern with preserved apical strain. ECG shows low voltage in the limb leads despite the wall thickness. Serum and urine immunofixation and serum free light-chain ratio are normal. Which of the following is the most appropriate next diagnostic step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Endomyocardial biopsy of the right ventricle"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Technetium-99m pyrophosphate (PYP) scintigraphy with SPECT"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Start empiric tafamidis 61 mg daily"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Coronary angiography"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Genetic testing for MYH7 mutations"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "The clinical picture (age, prior bilateral carpal tunnel, LVH with paradoxically low ECG voltage, biatrial enlargement, apical-sparing GLS 'cherry-on-top') is classic for transthyretin cardiac amyloidosis. Because monoclonal light chains have already been excluded with a normal free light-chain ratio and negative serum/urine immunofixation, a grade 2-3 myocardial PYP scan is diagnostic of ATTR-CM without the need for biopsy. Tafamidis (choice C) should not be started before the diagnosis is confirmed and AL amyloid excluded. Endomyocardial biopsy (A) is reserved for equivocal cases or when a monoclonal protein is present. Genetic testing (E) follows a confirmed ATTR diagnosis to distinguish wild-type from hereditary (variant) disease."}, {"stem": "A 24-year-old asymptomatic man is referred after his brother died suddenly. Echo shows asymmetric septal hypertrophy of 32 mm, resting LVOT gradient 20 mmHg rising to 90 mmHg with Valsalva, and no prior syncope. 48-hour Holter shows a run of nonsustained VT. Cardiac MRI shows extensive late gadolinium enhancement involving >20% of LV mass. Which feature is the strongest single indication to offer a primary-prevention ICD under the 2024 AHA/ACC HCM guideline?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Resting LVOT gradient that increases with Valsalva"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Maximal LV wall thickness of 32 mm"}, {"key": "C", "text": "His age of 24 years"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Absence of syncope"}, {"key": "E", "text": "New York Heart Association class I symptoms"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Massive LV hypertrophy (maximal wall thickness at least 30 mm) is a major, guideline-recognized risk marker for sudden cardiac death in HCM and, together with a family history of SCD, unexplained syncope, extensive LGE (at least 15% of LV mass), NSVT, and LV apical aneurysm or EF <50%, supports offering a primary-prevention ICD. This patient has several: wall thickness 32 mm, a first-degree relative with SCD, NSVT, and extensive LGE. LVOT obstruction and its provocation (A) drive symptoms but are not independent SCD risk markers. Young age and absence of symptoms do not lower the risk conferred by these markers."}, {"stem": "A 59-year-old woman with obstructive HCM remains dyspneic (NYHA III) with a resting LVOT gradient of 70 mmHg despite maximally tolerated metoprolol. She has an LVEF of 65%. You are considering mavacamten. Which statement about initiating and monitoring mavacamten is correct?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "It can be co-prescribed freely with strong CYP2D6 and CYP3A4 inhibitors without dose change"}, {"key": "B", "text": "It is dispensed through a REMS program because of the risk of systolic dysfunction and heart failure, with serial echocardiographic LVEF monitoring"}, {"key": "C", "text": "It should be started only after LVEF has fallen below 50%"}, {"key": "D", "text": "It increases myocardial contractility by sensitizing myofilaments to calcium"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Pregnancy is an acceptable time to continue therapy"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Mavacamten is a cardiac myosin inhibitor that reduces actin-myosin cross-bridge formation, lowering hypercontractility and LVOT gradient (so it decreases, not increases, contractility, making D wrong). Because excessive effect can cause reversible systolic dysfunction, it is available only through a REMS program requiring baseline and serial echocardiograms (assessing LVEF and gradient at weeks 4, 8, and 12 during initiation, then every 12 weeks) and dose interruption if LVEF falls below 50%. It is a CYP2D6/3A4 substrate, so concomitant strong inhibitors require dose adjustment or avoidance (A wrong). It is contraindicated in pregnancy (teratogenic; E wrong). It requires a preserved LVEF (at least 55%) to initiate, not withholding until dysfunction develops (C wrong)."}, {"stem": "A 46-year-old man presents with heart failure and new second-degree AV block. Echo shows mildly reduced LVEF (48%) with regional wall-thinning of the basal septum and an aneurysm. Cardiac PET shows patchy focal FDG uptake with a matched resting perfusion defect, and chest imaging shows mediastinal and hilar lymphadenopathy. Which of the following is the most appropriate management consideration?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "This is almost certainly ischemic cardiomyopathy; proceed to revascularization"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Immunosuppression with corticosteroids and early consideration of an ICD given conduction disease and arrhythmic risk"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Start tafamidis for presumed ATTR amyloid"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Reassure and repeat echo in one year"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Begin high-dose diuresis alone and avoid device therapy"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Basal septal thinning/aneurysm, high-grade AV block in a middle-aged patient, patchy FDG uptake on cardiac PET, and thoracic lymphadenopathy point strongly to cardiac sarcoidosis. Management combines immunosuppression (corticosteroids are first-line to suppress active inflammation) with arrhythmia risk mitigation: cardiac sarcoid causes conduction disease and ventricular arrhythmias, and consensus guidance lowers the threshold for ICD implantation (for example, in patients needing a permanent pacemaker or with unexplained syncope, LVEF <=35%, or inducible sustained VT). It is neither typical ischemic disease nor amyloidosis, and observation or diuresis alone would neglect the substantial risk of sudden death."}, {"stem": "A 55-year-old woman has exertional dyspnea and edema. Echo shows normal wall thickness, normal LVEF, and severe biatrial enlargement. At catheterization, the RV and LV diastolic pressures show a dip-and-plateau ('square root') morphology. Which finding at hemodynamic study would most favor CONSTRICTIVE PERICARDITIS over RESTRICTIVE CARDIOMYOPATHY?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Discordance of RV and LV systolic pressures with respiration (ventricular interdependence)"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Markedly elevated BNP"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Equalization of end-diastolic pressures across all chambers"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Elevated pulmonary artery systolic pressure of 60 mmHg"}, {"key": "E", "text": "A prominent y-descent on the RA tracing"}, {"key": "F", "text": "Preserved LVEF"}], "correct": "A", "explanation": "Both conditions cause a dip-and-plateau, elevated filling pressures, prominent y-descent, and preserved systolic function, so those features (C, E, F) do not discriminate. The hallmark of constriction is enhanced ventricular interdependence: with inspiration, LV filling falls and RV filling rises, producing discordant (out-of-phase) LV and RV systolic pressures across the respiratory cycle (quantified by the systolic area index). Restriction, by contrast, shows concordant respiratory changes and usually higher PA pressures and markedly elevated BNP. High PA systolic pressure (D) and very high BNP (B) actually favor restriction. Recognizing constriction matters because pericardiectomy can be curative."}], "sections": [{"id": "classification", "title": "Framework: phenotype first, then etiology", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "A cardiomyopathy is a structural and functional myocardial disorder not explained by loading conditions or coronary disease sufficient to cause the observed abnormality. In practice you reason in two moves. First, assign a <strong>morphofunctional phenotype</strong> from imaging: hypertrophic, dilated, restrictive, arrhythmogenic (right, left, or biventricular), or non-dilated left ventricular. Second, pursue the <strong>etiology</strong> behind that phenotype, because two patients with identical wall thickness can have sarcomeric HCM, ATTR amyloid, Fabry disease, or an athlete's heart, and the treatments diverge completely."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Hypertrophic (HCM)", "def": "Increased LV wall thickness (typically >=15 mm, or >=13 mm with family history or a positive genotype) not solely explained by abnormal loading. Classically sarcomeric, but phenocopies exist (amyloid, Fabry, storage disease)."}, {"term": "Dilated (DCM)", "def": "LV dilation and systolic dysfunction not explained by abnormal loading or coronary disease. Genetic, inflammatory, toxic, peripartum, tachycardia-mediated."}, {"term": "Restrictive (RCM)", "def": "Restrictive physiology (impaired filling, small/normal cavity, biatrial enlargement) with normal or near-normal wall thickness and EF. Infiltrative, storage, endomyocardial, and idiopathic causes."}, {"term": "Arrhythmogenic (ACM/ARVC)", "def": "Fibrofatty replacement predisposing to ventricular arrhythmia, often out of proportion to ventricular dysfunction; right, left-dominant, or biventricular."}, {"term": "Non-dilated LV cardiomyopathy (NDLVC)", "def": "An ESC 2023 category: non-dilated LV with scar/fibrosis or hypokinesis not fitting the other buckets, capturing many genetic/inflammatory phenotypes."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic - the restrictive/thick-walled mimics: \"FASHION.\"</strong> <strong>F</strong>abry, <strong>A</strong>myloid, <strong>S</strong>arcoid, <strong>H</strong>emochromatosis, <strong>I</strong>diopathic/inflammatory, <strong>O</strong>xalosis/storage (Danon, Pompe), <strong>N</strong>eoplastic/radiation. When a ventricle looks thick or stiff, walk this list before you call it sarcomeric HCM."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The ESC 2023 cardiomyopathy guideline deliberately abandoned the old \"primary vs secondary\" and \"specific cardiomyopathy\" language in favor of a phenotype-to-etiology pathway that integrates multimodality imaging and genetics. When you present a case, lead with the phenotype and the specific red flags that point toward an etiology rather than a generic label; this is the register expected at fellowship level."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "For labeled cardiac MRI and echo phenotypes across the cardiomyopathies (LGE patterns, apical sparing strain maps, RV involvement), use a curated imaging reference and correlate the described findings with cases.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia - cardiomyopathy imaging"}]}, {"id": "hcm-genetics-phenotype", "title": "HCM: genetics and phenotype", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "HCM is the most common inherited cardiomyopathy (roughly 1 in 500 in the general population by phenotype, and likely closer to 1 in 200 when subclinical genotype-positive individuals are counted). It is an autosomal-dominant disease of the sarcomere: the two most common culprit genes are <strong>MYBPC3</strong> (myosin-binding protein C) and <strong>MYH7</strong> (beta-myosin heavy chain). The defining lesion is unexplained LV hypertrophy, most often asymmetric and septal, with myocyte disarray and interstitial fibrosis that create both diastolic dysfunction and an arrhythmic substrate."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Phenotype is heterogeneous. Beyond classic asymmetric septal hypertrophy you will see apical HCM (giant T-wave inversions, spade-shaped cavity, and a risk of apical aneurysm), midcavitary obstruction, and burnt-out (end-stage) HCM with wall thinning and systolic dysfunction. Recognizing the pattern matters because apical aneurysm and systolic dysfunction (EF <50%) are themselves sudden-death and thromboembolic risk markers."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Clues that a thick-walled ventricle is NOT sarcomeric HCM", "head": ["Feature", "Points toward"], "rows": [["Low ECG voltage despite thick walls, apical-sparing GLS", "Amyloidosis (AL or ATTR)"], ["Short PR, high voltage, skeletal myopathy, WPW-type pre-excitation", "Danon / PRKAG2 / Pompe (glycogen storage)"], ["Concentric LVH, acroparesthesias, angiokeratoma, renal/corneal signs", "Fabry disease (low alpha-galactosidase A activity)"], ["Basal septal thinning, AV block, patchy scar", "Cardiac sarcoidosis"], ["Symmetric LVH regressing with detraining, EF/GLS normal, high VO2", "Athlete's heart"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic - the \"amyloid pretending to be HCM\" tell:</strong> thick walls but <strong>small QRS</strong>. Voltage-to-mass mismatch (increased wall thickness with low or normal ECG voltage) should trigger an amyloid workup before you anchor on HCM."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Genotype-positive/phenotype-negative relatives (sarcomere variant carriers with normal imaging) are not diagnosed with HCM but require longitudinal surveillance because penetrance is age-dependent and incomplete. Do not clear them; enroll them in serial imaging."}]}, {"id": "hcm-lvot", "title": "HCM: LVOT obstruction physiology", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "About two-thirds of HCM patients have obstruction, at rest or provocable. The mechanism is dynamic. A hypertrophied basal septum narrows the outflow tract, accelerating flow that drags the anterior mitral leaflet toward the septum (<strong>systolic anterior motion, SAM</strong>) by a Venturi/drag effect. SAM both obstructs the outflow tract and pulls the leaflets apart, producing a posteriorly directed mitral regurgitation jet. The gradient is therefore <strong>dynamic</strong>: it worsens with anything that reduces preload/afterload or increases contractility, and improves with the opposite."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "What moves the dynamic LVOT gradient", "head": ["Increases gradient (worse)", "Decreases gradient (better)"], "rows": [["Decreased preload (Valsalva strain, standing, dehydration, nitrates, diuretics)", "Increased preload (squatting, leg raise, volume)"], ["Decreased afterload (vasodilators, sepsis)", "Increased afterload (handgrip, phenylephrine, squatting)"], ["Increased contractility (exercise, dobutamine, digoxin, inotropes)", "Negative inotropes (beta-blockers, verapamil, disopyramide, mavacamten)"], ["Tachycardia (shortened diastole)", "Bradycardia / rate control"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "In obstructive HCM, avoid or use extreme caution with vasodilators (dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers, ACE inhibitors/ARBs when hypotensive, nitrates) and pure inotropes. Reducing afterload or augmenting contractility can precipitate severe outflow obstruction, hypotension, and syncope. Treat hypotension with fluids and phenylephrine, not with pure inotropes."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Bedside/echo provocation to unmask latent obstruction", "items": ["Measure the resting LVOT gradient by continuous-wave Doppler (dagger-shaped, late-peaking systolic envelope).", "If the resting gradient is <50 mmHg and the patient is symptomatic, provoke: Valsalva strain phase, then standing from squat.", "If still <50 mmHg and symptoms are exertional, perform exercise (treadmill or supine bicycle) stress echocardiography - the most physiologic provocation.", "A peak instantaneous gradient >=30 mmHg defines obstruction; >=50 mmHg (rest or provoked) is the threshold for invasive septal reduction when symptoms persist.", "Distinguish true LVOT signal from mitral regurgitation and midcavitary obstruction by envelope timing and shape."]}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "For the apical HCM ECG (giant precordial T-wave inversions) and other named HCM ECG patterns, review a labeled ECG library.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG library - HCM patterns"}]}, {"id": "hcm-scd", "title": "HCM: sudden death risk stratification", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "HCM is a leading cause of sudden cardiac death in the young, but the absolute annual risk in an unselected population is low (well under 1% per year). The task is to identify the minority at meaningfully elevated risk who benefit from a primary-prevention ICD, without over-implanting. The 2020/2024 ACC/AHA approach is a <strong>risk-marker</strong> model; the ESC uses a continuous <strong>HCM Risk-SCD score</strong>. Know both."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "ACC/AHA major SCD risk markers in HCM (each supports considering a primary-prevention ICD)", "head": ["Marker", "Threshold / definition"], "rows": [["Family history of SCD", "Sudden death judged HCM-related in >=1 first-degree or close relative, usually <50 yr"], ["Massive LV hypertrophy", "Maximal wall thickness >=30 mm (>=28 mm may weigh in with other factors)"], ["Unexplained syncope", "Recent (within ~6 months), not clearly neurocardiogenic"], ["Nonsustained VT", "On ambulatory monitoring, especially frequent/longer/faster runs"], ["LV apical aneurysm", "Regardless of size"], ["LV systolic dysfunction", "LVEF <50%"], ["Extensive LGE on CMR", "Late gadolinium enhancement >=15% of LV mass (risk modifier)"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "ESC HCM Risk-SCD", "def": "A validated equation estimating 5-year SCD risk from age, maximal wall thickness, left atrial diameter, maximal LVOT gradient, family history of SCD, NSVT, and unexplained syncope. Roughly: <4% low, 4-6% intermediate, >=6% high (ICD reasonable). It is not validated in children, elite athletes, or metabolic/infiltrative phenocopies."}, {"term": "Role of CMR-LGE", "def": "Extensive LGE (>=15% LV mass) reclassifies intermediate-risk patients upward and is embedded in shared decision-making; the 2024 guideline elevated its role alongside LV apical aneurysm and LVEF <50%."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The two systems can disagree, particularly in the young, where the ESC score may under-call risk. The 2024 guideline emphasizes shared decision-making and lets a single strong marker (for example, massive hypertrophy, apical aneurysm, or an HCM-related family SCD) justify an ICD even when a score reads 'low.' Document the individualized reasoning. Note that LVOT gradient severity and NYHA class are drivers of symptoms, not standalone SCD indications."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic - HCM SCD red flags: \"FAT VAN.\"</strong> <strong>F</strong>amily history of SCD, <strong>A</strong>bnormal (massive) wall thickness >=30 mm, <strong>T</strong>hickness-plus-LGE (extensive fibrosis), <strong>V</strong>T (nonsustained), <strong>A</strong>neurysm (apical) or EF<50%, <strong>N</strong>o-cause syncope."}]}, {"id": "hcm-therapy", "title": "HCM: medical therapy, mavacamten, and septal reduction", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "For symptomatic obstructive HCM the sequence is: negative inotropy first (beta-blocker, then verapamil/diltiazem or disopyramide), then a cardiac myosin inhibitor or invasive septal reduction if symptoms persist. Non-obstructive symptomatic HCM is treated for diastolic heart failure and comorbid arrhythmia; if it progresses to systolic dysfunction, treat as guideline-directed HFrEF."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Pharmacologic therapy of obstructive HCM", "head": ["Drug / class", "Mechanism", "Start dose", "Target / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Major adverse effects", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Metoprolol / other beta-blocker", "Negative inotrope + chronotrope, blunts exercise gradient", "Metoprolol succinate 25-50 mg daily", "Up-titrate to HR/symptom control (e.g., 100-200 mg daily)", "Severe bradycardia, high-grade AV block, decompensated HF", "Fatigue, bradycardia, bronchospasm", "HR, BP, symptoms"], ["Verapamil / diltiazem", "Non-dihydropyridine CCB, negative inotrope", "Verapamil 40-80 mg TID (or extended-release)", "120-480 mg daily", "Use with caution/avoid if resting gradient very high, hypotension, or elevated PCWP; caution combining with beta-blocker", "Bradycardia, AV block, hypotension, constipation", "HR, BP; avoid in advanced obstruction/pulmonary congestion"], ["Disopyramide", "Class Ia antiarrhythmic; potent negative inotrope reducing SAM", "100-150 mg BID (add to beta-blocker/CCB)", "Up to ~400-600 mg/day (divided)", "QT prolongation, glaucoma, urinary retention", "Anticholinergic (dry mouth, retention), QT prolongation", "QTc; pair with an AV-nodal agent because vagolytic effect may speed AV conduction in AF"], ["Mavacamten", "Cardiac myosin inhibitor; reduces actin-myosin cross-bridges and hypercontractility", "2.5-5 mg once daily", "Titrate by echo LVEF/gradient (2.5-15 mg once daily) per REMS", "Concomitant strong CYP2D6/3A4 inhibitors; pregnancy; LVEF <55% at initiation", "Reversible reduction in LVEF/systolic dysfunction, heart failure, AF", "REMS: baseline and serial echo LVEF (weeks 4/8/12 during initiation, then every 12 weeks); interrupt if LVEF <50%"], ["Diuretics (cautious)", "Reduce congestion", "Low dose", "Lowest effective", "Volume depletion worsens dynamic obstruction", "Hypotension, gradient rise", "Volume status, BP"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "Mavacamten (EXPLORER-HCM, VALOR-HCM)", "def": "First-in-class cardiac myosin inhibitor. EXPLORER-HCM showed improved exercise capacity, symptoms, and LVOT gradient in symptomatic obstructive HCM; VALOR-HCM showed it reduced the proportion of patients meeting septal-reduction criteria. Dispensed only through a REMS because of the risk of systolic dysfunction; requires LVEF >=55% to initiate, with baseline and scheduled echocardiographic LVEF surveillance and dose interruption if LVEF <50%. CYP2D6/3A4 substrate with drug-interaction and pharmacogenomic dosing considerations; teratogenic."}, {"term": "Aficamten (SEQUOIA-HCM)", "def": "A next-generation cardiac myosin inhibitor with a shorter half-life and potentially simpler titration; SEQUOIA-HCM showed improved peak VO2 and gradient in obstructive HCM. Know it exists as the class expands (under regulatory review at the time of writing)."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Invasive septal reduction therapy (for drug-refractory symptomatic obstruction, gradient >=50 mmHg)", "head": ["Modality", "Best candidate", "Key risks", "Notes"], "rows": [["Surgical septal myectomy (Morrow)", "Younger patients, very thick septum, concomitant mitral/other surgery needed; performed at expert centers", "Bleeding, VSD (rare), AR, conduction disease", "Guideline-preferred at experienced HCM centers; durable gradient relief"], ["Alcohol septal ablation", "Older/higher surgical risk, suitable septal perforator anatomy", "Complete heart block needing pacemaker, variable MI size", "Avoid if septum very thick or unfavorable coronary anatomy"], ["Dual-chamber pacing", "Selected patients unsuitable for myectomy/ablation", "Limited efficacy", "Generally adjunctive/second-line"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Septal reduction is for <strong>symptoms</strong>, not prognosis, and belongs at high-volume HCM centers where operative mortality for isolated myectomy is very low. Refer early rather than escalating drugs indefinitely in a highly symptomatic obstructed patient."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Atrial fibrillation is poorly tolerated in HCM because of preload dependence and impaired filling. Anticoagulate HCM patients with AF regardless of CHA2DS2-VASc score, and prioritize rate/rhythm control. Competitive athletics and burst high-intensity exertion decisions are individualized under the updated guideline's shared-decision framework."}]}, {"id": "dcm", "title": "Dilated cardiomyopathy: a genetics-and-reversibility mindset", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "DCM is LV (or biventricular) dilation with systolic dysfunction after excluding ischemia and abnormal loading. Roughly a third are genetic. The two clinical imperatives are (1) hunt for a reversible or specific driver and (2) test for high-arrhythmic-risk genotypes that change device decisions independent of EF."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "Reversible / specific DCM drivers to exclude", "items": ["Tachycardia-mediated (chronic AF/flutter, frequent PVCs) - rhythm control or PVC suppression can normalize EF", "Toxic: alcohol, anthracyclines/HER2 agents, cocaine/methamphetamine, immune-checkpoint-inhibitor myocarditis", "Inflammatory/infiltrative: giant-cell myocarditis (fulminant, needs biopsy and immunosuppression), sarcoid, lymphocytic myocarditis", "Endocrine/nutritional: thyroid disease, thiamine deficiency (wet beriberi), pheochromocytoma, acromegaly", "Peripartum cardiomyopathy (late pregnancy to months postpartum)", "Stress (takotsubo) - apical ballooning with wall-motion beyond a single coronary territory, usually reversible"]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 3, "caption": "DCM genotypes that alter arrhythmic risk and device timing", "head": ["Gene", "Signature", "Implication"], "rows": [["LMNA (lamin A/C)", "Conduction disease + AF + DCM, often family history of SCD/pacemakers", "High SCD risk; consider ICD at higher EF thresholds per risk score, not just EF<=35%"], ["Desmosomal (PKP2, DSP, etc.)", "Left-dominant/arrhythmogenic phenotype, LGE", "Arrhythmic risk out of proportion to EF; overlaps ARVC/ACM"], ["FLNC (truncating), RBM20", "High arrhythmic burden, fibrosis", "Elevated SCD risk; earlier ICD consideration"], ["TTN truncating", "Most common DCM variant", "Often more favorable, better reverse-remodeling response"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "For 'high-risk genotype' DCM (LMNA, FLNC-truncating, desmosomal, RBM20), guidelines and consensus support considering an ICD before EF reaches the conventional <=35% threshold, using dedicated risk tools (for example, the LMNA-risk calculator incorporating NSVT, high-grade AV block, male sex, and degree of LV dysfunction). This is a frequent fellowship discriminator: EF alone under-protects these patients."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Otherwise, treat DCM with full guideline-directed medical therapy for HFrEF (ARNI or ACEi/ARB, beta-blocker, MRA, SGLT2 inhibitor), device therapy per EF/QRS, and wearable defibrillators as a bridge in select recently diagnosed patients while awaiting reverse remodeling."}]}, {"id": "restrictive-overview", "title": "Restrictive and infiltrative cardiomyopathies", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Restrictive physiology means a stiff, non-compliant ventricle that fills at high pressure through a small cavity, driving biatrial enlargement, elevated filling pressures, and right-heart congestion out of proportion to a normal-sized, often normally contracting LV. The classic bedside picture is right-sided failure (elevated JVP, ascites, edema) with preserved EF and small ventricles."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Etiologies of restrictive cardiomyopathy", "head": ["Category", "Examples", "Diagnostic anchor"], "rows": [["Infiltrative", "Amyloidosis (ATTR, AL), sarcoidosis", "Bone scintigraphy (PYP) + light chains; cardiac PET/MRI"], ["Storage", "Hemochromatosis, Fabry, glycogen storage (Danon, Pompe)", "Ferritin/transferrin saturation; alpha-Gal A; enzyme/genetics; T2* MRI for iron"], ["Endomyocardial", "Endomyocardial fibrosis, hypereosinophilic (Loffler) endocarditis, carcinoid", "Eosinophil count; apical obliteration/thrombus"], ["Other", "Radiation, scleroderma, idiopathic", "History; imaging"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic - hemochromatosis is the treatable restrictive/dilated overlap.</strong> Check <strong>iron studies (ferritin, transferrin saturation)</strong> in any unexplained cardiomyopathy: cardiac MRI T2* quantifies iron and phlebotomy/chelation can reverse dysfunction if caught early."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "Loffler endocarditis and endomyocardial fibrosis show characteristic apical obliteration and mural thrombus; correlate the described echo/MRI features with a labeled imaging case set.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia - restrictive cardiomyopathy imaging"}]}, {"id": "amyloid", "title": "Cardiac amyloidosis: recognize, type, and treat", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Cardiac amyloidosis is now a can't-miss diagnosis because effective therapy exists. Misfolded protein deposits in the interstitium stiffen the myocardium. Two types dominate the heart: <strong>ATTR</strong> (transthyretin, either wild-type/senile or hereditary variant) and <strong>AL</strong> (immunoglobulin light chain, a plasma-cell dyscrasia and an oncologic emergency). Distinguishing them is the pivotal step: AL requires urgent hematology/chemotherapy, while ATTR is treated with a transthyretin stabilizer or gene silencer."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "Red flags that should trigger an amyloid workup", "items": ["LVH on echo with low or discordantly normal ECG voltage (voltage-mass mismatch)", "Apical-sparing longitudinal strain ('cherry on top' bull's-eye map)", "Bilateral carpal tunnel syndrome, lumbar spinal stenosis, or spontaneous biceps tendon rupture (years before cardiac symptoms)", "HFpEF with intolerance to standard doses of beta-blockers/ACE inhibitors and unexplained hypotension", "Discordant troponin/NT-proBNP elevation, conduction disease, low-flow low-gradient aortic stenosis in an older adult", "Autonomic neuropathy or polyneuropathy (especially in hereditary ATTR)"]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Diagnostic algorithm for suspected cardiac amyloidosis", "items": ["Suspect based on red flags + echo/CMR (increased wall thickness, granular myocardium, apical-sparing GLS, diffuse subendocardial-to-transmural LGE, elevated native T1 and extracellular volume).", "Screen for a monoclonal protein FIRST: serum and urine immunofixation electrophoresis AND serum free light-chain ratio. This must be done in every case.", "If monoclonal protein testing is NEGATIVE and a technetium-99m PYP (or DPD/HMDP) bone scintigraphy scan shows grade 2-3 myocardial uptake (heart-to-contralateral ratio >=1.5 at 1 hour), you can diagnose ATTR-CM non-invasively - no biopsy needed.", "If ANY monoclonal protein is present, or PYP is equivocal, obtain tissue: endomyocardial biopsy (near 100% sensitive) with Congo red (apple-green birefringence) and mass-spectrometry typing. Never rely on PYP alone when light chains are abnormal - AL can also take up tracer.", "Once ATTR is confirmed, perform TTR genetic testing to separate hereditary (variant) from wild-type disease and enable family screening."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "A positive PYP scan does NOT by itself prove ATTR. AL amyloid can show myocardial tracer uptake, and missing an AL diagnosis (a rapidly fatal plasma-cell disease) to start an ATTR drug is a serious error. The light-chain screen is mandatory and comes first."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Disease-modifying therapy in cardiac amyloidosis", "head": ["Agent", "Type", "Mechanism", "Dose", "Key points / monitoring"], "rows": [["Tafamidis (ATTR-ACT)", "ATTR-CM", "TTR tetramer stabilizer", "61 mg (free acid) once daily, or 80 mg meglumine once daily", "Reduced all-cause mortality and CV hospitalization in ATTR-CM; benefit greatest in NYHA I-II; well tolerated"], ["Acoramidis (ATTRibute-CM)", "ATTR-CM", "Near-complete TTR stabilizer", "712 mg (two 356 mg tablets) twice daily", "FDA-approved 2024; reduced CV death and CV-related hospitalization; near-complete TTR stabilization"], ["Vutrisiran (HELIOS-B)", "ATTR-CM (and hATTR-PN)", "TTR gene silencing (RNAi), reduces hepatic TTR production", "25 mg subcutaneously every 3 months", "FDA-approved for ATTR-CM 2025; reduced all-cause mortality and CV events; also approved for polyneuropathy"], ["Patisiran", "hATTR polyneuropathy (RNAi)", "TTR gene silencing (RNAi)", "IV every 3 weeks per label", "Approved for hATTR-PN; cardiac endpoint data did not lead to a CM indication"], ["Diflunisal (off-label)", "ATTR", "NSAID-class stabilizer", "Cautious use", "Renal/GI/bleeding risk; limits use in HF"], ["AL-directed chemo (e.g., daratumumab-based CyBorD)", "AL", "Eradicate clonal plasma cells", "Hematology-directed", "Urgent; goal is deep hematologic response; not tafamidis"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Managing the failing amyloid heart: these patients are preload-dependent and rate-dependent. Beta-blockers and non-dihydropyridine CCBs are often poorly tolerated (CCBs can bind amyloid fibrils and cause profound hypotension/heart block - avoid). Digoxin binds amyloid fibrils and is used cautiously if at all. Diurese carefully for congestion, and anticoagulate for AF (and consider it even in sinus rhythm with atrial mechanical dysfunction/thrombus given high embolic risk)."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic - the amyloid 'soft signs' cluster: think amyloid when the hands and back complain before the heart does.</strong> Bilateral <strong>carpal tunnel</strong> + <strong>lumbar stenosis</strong> + <strong>biceps tendon rupture</strong> in an older adult with HFpEF and thick walls = ATTR until proven otherwise."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "The apical-sparing 'cherry-on-top' strain bull's-eye and diffuse subendocardial LGE are the imaging signatures; correlate with labeled multimodality cases.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia - cardiac amyloidosis"}]}, {"id": "sarcoid", "title": "Cardiac sarcoidosis", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Cardiac sarcoidosis is patchy non-caseating granulomatous inflammation that produces a triad of problems: conduction disease (AV block in a relatively young patient is a classic presentation), ventricular arrhythmias, and heart failure. Cardiac involvement drives most sarcoid mortality and is frequently under-recognized because systemic disease may be silent."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "When to actively suspect cardiac sarcoid", "items": ["Unexplained high-grade AV block or new pacemaker need in an adult younger than ~60", "Unexplained sustained VT or frequent ventricular ectopy without CAD", "New nonischemic cardiomyopathy with regional wall-motion abnormalities that don't respect a coronary territory", "Basal septal thinning or aneurysm on imaging", "Known extracardiac sarcoidosis with any cardiac symptom"]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Diagnostic workup", "items": ["ECG, echo, and ambulatory monitoring to capture conduction disease and arrhythmia.", "Cardiac MRI: mid-wall/epicardial and basal-septal LGE, edema on T2.", "FDG-PET after a high-fat/low-carb (or prolonged fasting) prep to suppress physiologic myocardial glucose uptake: patchy focal FDG uptake, especially with a matched resting perfusion defect, indicates active inflammation and guides immunosuppression response.", "Search for extracardiac disease to obtain a safer biopsy target (mediastinal/hilar nodes, lung); endomyocardial biopsy has low yield because involvement is patchy (consider electroanatomic- or imaging-guided biopsy).", "Apply consensus (HRS) diagnostic criteria integrating histology and imaging."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Management pillars of cardiac sarcoidosis", "head": ["Problem", "Approach"], "rows": [["Active inflammation", "Corticosteroids first-line; steroid-sparing agents (methotrexate, azathioprine, mycophenolate, anti-TNF) for chronic control; track response by FDG-PET"], ["Conduction disease", "Pacemaker; given arrhythmic substrate, favor a device with defibrillator capability when criteria met"], ["Ventricular arrhythmia / SCD risk", "ICD for VT, LVEF <=35%, unexplained syncope, need for permanent pacing, or inducible sustained VT; antiarrhythmics/ablation for refractory VT"], ["Heart failure", "Standard guideline-directed medical therapy"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Do not treat isolated high-grade AV block in a young adult as routine and simply implant a plain pacemaker without asking why. Missing cardiac sarcoid (or Lyme carditis, or a lamin cardiomyopathy) forgoes immunosuppression and under-protects against sudden death - the substrate for lethal VT is present even when EF looks preserved."}]}, {"id": "restrictive-vs-constrictive", "title": "Restrictive cardiomyopathy vs constrictive pericarditis", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "This is one of the highest-yield distinctions in cardiology because the presentations overlap (right-heart failure, preserved EF, elevated and equalized filling pressures, dip-and-plateau) but the treatments diverge: constriction is potentially cured by pericardiectomy, whereas restriction is managed medically. The unifying concept: constriction has a rigid pericardial shell producing <strong>enhanced ventricular interdependence</strong> and <strong>dissociation of intrathoracic and intracardiac pressures</strong>; restriction is intrinsic myocardial stiffness without those respiratory dynamics."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Discriminating features", "head": ["Feature", "Constrictive pericarditis", "Restrictive cardiomyopathy"], "rows": [["Ventricular interdependence", "Present - discordant RV/LV systolic pressures with respiration", "Absent - concordant"], ["Respiratory variation in mitral inflow", "Marked (>25%)", "Minimal"], ["Septal bounce / annulus reversus", "Yes; medial e' preserved or increased (annulus reversus)", "No; medial e' reduced (impaired relaxation)"], ["Pulmonary artery systolic pressure", "Usually <55 mmHg", "Often higher (>55 mmHg)"], ["BNP/NT-proBNP", "Relatively lower", "Markedly elevated"], ["Pericardium", "Thickened/calcified (CT/MRI); tethering", "Normal"], ["Hepatic vein Doppler", "Expiratory diastolic flow reversal", "Inspiratory reversal"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 3, "entries": [{"term": "Annulus reversus", "def": "In constriction, longitudinal (annular) function is spared while radial is limited by the shell, so medial tissue-Doppler e' is paradoxically higher than lateral e' - the reverse of most myocardial disease. A useful echo discriminator."}, {"term": "Dip-and-plateau / square-root sign", "def": "Rapid early diastolic filling then abrupt cessation as the stiff chamber or rigid pericardium halts filling. Seen in BOTH conditions, so it does not discriminate."}, {"term": "Ventricular interdependence", "def": "With a fixed pericardial volume, inspiratory augmentation of RV filling occurs at the expense of LV filling (and vice versa), producing out-of-phase (discordant) ventricular systolic pressures - the invasive hallmark of constriction."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "When echo is equivocal, invasive simultaneous LV/RV hemodynamics with the <strong>systolic area index</strong> (ratio of RV to LV systolic pressure-time area in inspiration vs expiration) is the most specific test for constriction. Remember amyloid can coexist and mimic restriction, so type the myocardium too."}]}, {"id": "arvc", "title": "Arrhythmogenic (right ventricular) cardiomyopathy", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy is progressive fibrofatty replacement of myocardium, classically the RV (ARVC) but increasingly recognized as left-dominant or biventricular (arrhythmogenic left ventricular cardiomyopathy). It is a disease of the <strong>desmosome</strong> (PKP2 most common; also DSP, DSG2, DSC2, JUP), causing ventricular arrhythmias and SCD, often in young athletes, sometimes before overt dysfunction. Exercise both unmasks and accelerates it."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Diagnosis uses the <strong>Task Force Criteria concept</strong>: no single test is diagnostic, so you accumulate evidence across six categories, each split into major and minor criteria, and a defined combination (for example, two major, or one major plus two minor, or four minor from different categories) establishes 'definite' ARVC. This weighted, multi-domain design is the exam-relevant idea - reproduce the categories, not memorized cutoffs."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Task Force Criteria domains (2010) - the conceptual scaffold", "head": ["Domain", "Representative findings"], "rows": [["Global/regional dysfunction & structural", "RV dilation, reduced RV EF, regional akinesia/dyskinesia/aneurysm (echo/MRI/angiography)"], ["Tissue characterization", "Fibrofatty replacement on endomyocardial biopsy (residual myocytes <60%)"], ["Repolarization abnormalities", "T-wave inversion in V1-V3 (beyond age norms, without complete RBBB)"], ["Depolarization/conduction", "Epsilon wave; late potentials on signal-averaged ECG; prolonged terminal activation duration"], ["Arrhythmias", "VT of LBBB morphology with superior axis (major) or other morphology/NSVT; frequent PVCs (>500/24h)"], ["Family history / genetics", "Confirmed ARVC or pathogenic desmosomal variant in a first-degree relative"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Epsilon wave", "def": "A small reproducible deflection in the ST segment (after the QRS) in right precordial leads (V1-V3), reflecting delayed RV activation - a specific but insensitive depolarization criterion."}, {"term": "Padua criteria (2020)", "def": "A proposed update expanding the Task Force framework to incorporate CMR tissue characterization (LGE) and explicitly include left-dominant/biventricular phenotypes, reflecting the shift from 'ARVC' to 'arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy.'"}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Counsel patients with (or at genetic risk for) arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy to <strong>avoid competitive and high-intensity endurance exercise</strong> - it is an independent driver of arrhythmia and structural progression. This is one of the few cardiomyopathies where exercise restriction is disease-modifying, not merely symptomatic."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "ICD decisions weigh prior sustained VT/aborted arrest (secondary prevention, clear indication) against primary-prevention markers: unexplained syncope, severe RV or LV dysfunction, NSVT, and inducibility. Beta-blockers are baseline; catheter ablation (often requiring an epicardial approach given the epicardial-to-endocardial fibrofatty gradient) treats recurrent VT but is rarely curative."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "Review the epsilon wave and anterior precordial T-wave inversion patterns of ARVC on a labeled ECG library.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG library - ARVC / epsilon wave"}]}, {"id": "genetics-screening", "title": "Genetics and family screening", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Most cardiomyopathies you will diagnose are heritable, so the index case is also a sentinel for a family. Two obligations follow every genetic or unexplained cardiomyopathy diagnosis: build a three-generation pedigree and arrange clinical screening of first-degree relatives, and offer genetic counseling and testing of the proband to enable cascade testing."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Family screening workflow", "items": ["Take a detailed three-generation family history including sudden death, unexplained drowning/car accidents, pacemakers/ICDs, transplants, and heart failure at young ages.", "Offer genetic counseling and test the proband (the most clearly affected family member) first to identify the causative variant.", "If a pathogenic/likely-pathogenic variant is found, perform cascade genetic testing of relatives: genotype-negative relatives can often be released from serial imaging; genotype-positive relatives enter surveillance.", "If no variant is identified (or testing is declined), screen first-degree relatives clinically (history, exam, ECG, echo) at intervals - more frequently through adolescence and young adulthood for HCM/ARVC because penetrance is age-dependent.", "Re-evaluate periodically; a normal study in a young relative does not exclude later phenotype development."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 3, "caption": "Genotype-phenotype anchors worth carrying", "head": ["Cardiomyopathy", "Common genes", "Practical hook"], "rows": [["HCM", "MYBPC3, MYH7", "Sarcomeric; age-dependent penetrance; screen relatives serially"], ["DCM", "TTN (truncating), LMNA, FLNC, RBM20, desmosomal", "LMNA/FLNC/desmosomal = high arrhythmic risk, earlier ICD"], ["ARVC / ACM", "PKP2, DSP, DSG2, DSC2, JUP", "Desmosomal; exercise restriction; DSP overlaps left-dominant"], ["Amyloid (hereditary ATTR)", "TTR variants (e.g., V122I, T60A)", "Confirm after ATTR diagnosis; enables family testing and neuropathy surveillance"], ["Fabry", "GLA (X-linked)", "Treatable with enzyme replacement; check alpha-Gal A (men) / genetics (women)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Test the sickest relative first.</strong> Testing an affected proband maximizes the chance of identifying a causative variant, which is what makes downstream cascade testing of unaffected relatives interpretable. A negative test in an unaffected relative is only reassuring once a family variant is known."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Variants of uncertain significance (VUS) are common and should NOT drive clinical decisions or cascade testing on their own; manage by phenotype and periodically re-query variant databases as classifications evolve. Coordinate through a multidisciplinary inherited-cardiomyopathy clinic when available."}]}, {"id": "putting-together", "title": "Integrated diagnostic approach", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Bringing it together: the workup of an unexplained cardiomyopathy is a disciplined convergence of the ECG, echo with strain, cardiac MRI, targeted labs, and (when indicated) nuclear imaging and genetics. The goal is to move from a phenotype to a specific, often treatable, etiology."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "A practical sequence for the undifferentiated cardiomyopathy", "items": ["Characterize the phenotype on echo with global longitudinal strain (look specifically for apical sparing).", "Read the ECG for the etiology-defining clues: low voltage vs high voltage, conduction disease, giant T-wave inversions, epsilon waves, short PR/pre-excitation.", "Screen labs directed by suspicion: iron studies, serum/urine immunofixation + free light chains, alpha-galactosidase A, thyroid, and BNP/troponin.", "Obtain cardiac MRI for tissue characterization (LGE pattern, T1/T2 mapping, ECV) - the LGE distribution is frequently diagnostic (diffuse subendocardial = amyloid; mid-wall/epicardial basal-septal = sarcoid; subepicardial lateral = myocarditis/DSP).", "Add technetium-PYP for suspected ATTR (after light-chain screen) and FDG-PET for suspected active sarcoid.", "Refer for genetic counseling/testing and family screening when a genetic cause is confirmed or the phenotype is unexplained.", "Reserve endomyocardial biopsy for specific scenarios: suspected giant-cell myocarditis, amyloid with an abnormal monoclonal protein, or rapidly progressive disease of unclear cause."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "The single most information-dense combination in modern cardiomyopathy workup is <strong>echo with GLS + cardiac MRI with mapping</strong>. Strain localizes and quantifies dysfunction before EF falls; MRI tissue characterization frequently hands you the etiology from the LGE pattern alone."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "For the full multimodality atlas of cardiomyopathy imaging (LGE patterns by disease, PYP grading, strain maps), correlate described findings with labeled cases.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia - cardiomyopathy multimodality atlas"}]}]};
